Captain Marvel actress Brie Larson boasted in a recent interview that Captain Marvel most definitely can lift Thor’s mythical hammer, Mjolnir, which requires whosoever to wield it to be worthy.

Larson spoke to BuzzFeed Brasil while attending Brazil’s massive comic-con, CCXP, this past weekend.

When asked on whether or not Captain Marvel would be able to pick up Mjolnir, Larson quickly nodded her…

summary: Captain Marvel and the future of the Avengers, explained
body:
Hey…

Did you know…

There’s an actual storyline or two in the comics where CAPTAIN MARVEL and The Avengers have teamed up?

“In the comic books, Carol and the Avengers have saved the universe on multiple occasions. And in 2015, Carol teamed up with Black Panther and a few other superheroes as the Ultimates, a team tasked with eliminating cosmic threats — basically an outfit seemingly designed in a lab specifically to take on Thanos. So there’s plenty of comics precedent for Carol Danvers facing the sort of situation at the end of Infinity War.”

Did you also remember what huge comic nerds the Russo Brothers are?

Yeah, for those already bitching about the possible plot line of Endgame, you might want to check the source material the Russo’s are working from before throwing a conniption fit in the tags. Just a thought. You might not like it, but it just might be in the comics.

Quotation Credit: https://www.vox.com/2018/5/14/17325708/avengers-infinity-war-captain-marvel-post-credits-larson

Captain Marvel and the future of the Avengers, explained

title: Dear Brie Larson,
body:
This is my open letter of sorts, if you will, to you, a feminist whiner-babe who can’t seem to understand that it’s not just “the patriarchy” that’s hating on your bad acting and your piece of garbage new starring role in the collapsing-in-on-itself-like-a-dying-star MCU.

I didn’t wait six years for a female superhero movie to get emotionless, expressionless, incapable-of-smiling-unless-it’s-like-a-smart-arse, correcting-men-needlessly, unrelatable Carl Manvers Carol Danvers.

I’d been hoping, keeping my fingers crossed, for a Black Widow* movie.

I don’t give a damn about Captain SJW/Feminist, Brie, and it’s not a man’s fault that I hate your character and that I dislike you. I don’t know you, but I just don’t like your personality; how you express yourself and how you talk down to men, who are better than you in every respect at their jobs, is tasteless and repulsive at ever turn– it shows your true character and it reveals to me that it’s not one I’d enjoy knowing; that’s your fault, not “the patriarchy’s”. And, let me tell you: I’ve never liked Danvers. She’s boring and flat and painfully poorly-written. (How could she be anything else in this age of feminism and political correctness?) But I do care about Nat. I can relate to Nat, I can identify with Nat, I love Nat. 

This blonde, petulant brat with convenient amnesia just feels like a slap in the face. “We don’t give a f*ck if you like Black Widow, here’s a new female that you’re supposed to like, so LIKE HER WE DEMAND IT!”

So I’m not going to see this movie. And honestly? I hope it bombs at the box office because it needs to. Maybe then Marvel will understand that they need to consider very carefully what they’re doing.

I’m a woman, and I do not want this character, Brie. Because of you.

*please note that I could’ve used one of the other many female characters in the MCU, such as Wasp, Wanda, Jane Foster, Valkyrie, Okoye, Shuri, etc, but I went with Natasha because she’s my favorite and I’ve been waiting for a movie for her since I became a fan.

summary: Not only did Brie Larson get strong enough to push a Jeep up a hill while training for Captain Marvel, but she did the majority...
body: Not only did Brie Larson get strong enough to push a Jeep up a hill while training for Captain Marvel, but she did the majority of her own stunts for the movie after training for 9 months and is sticking with practicing judo and boxing because she loves it. And she did all that without fully realizing that someone else would be available to double for her. She just was like, “Well if Carol can kick so much ass, then I wanna be able to do it?” So when you see all the intense stuff being done in the movie… yeah, Brie Larson can just DO that lol.
